{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649206"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:02:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:02:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18354"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18354"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11072"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74719"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11072"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18354"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60203"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25850"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74719"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of different nerves responsible for the cutaneous innervation of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following areas does the saphenous nerve provide sensory innervation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plantar surface of the foot","Lateral aspect of the foot","Medial aspect of the foot","Dorsum of the foot","Heel of the foot"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe saphenous nerve is a branch of the femoral nerve and is part of the lumbar plexus. It travels down the leg and provides sensory innervation to specific areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe saphenous nerve provides sensory innervation to the \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial aspect of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E. It is a continuation of the femoral nerve and supplies sensation to the medial side of the leg and foot. The other areas are innervated by different nerves:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral aspect of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - Innervated by the sural nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorsum of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - Primarily innervated by the superficial fibular nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlantar surface of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - Innervated by the medial and lateral plantar nerves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeel of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - Innervated by the tibial nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The saphenous nerve provides sensory innervation to the medial aspect of the foot.","The saphenous nerve is a branch of the femoral nerve, which is part of the lumbar plexus.","The saphenous nerve does not provide motor innervation to the foot."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R,